story:
On the 12th June 2021 I’ll be competing in the Ultra Challenge in the Lake District. I’ll be walking (maybe jogging a bit!?) 49KM from Kendal to Windermere with a 1300m climb. Starting at 7am and finishing (hopefully) before dark! 

We all know someone whose lives have been affected by cancer. Macmillan Cancer Support are such a wonderful charity! They sadly expect to lose almost £100m in voluntary income this year as a result of the coronavirus crisis. 

With their annual coffee morning being cancelled this year I decided to compete in a challenge to raise money to this wonderful charity! 

Thanks for supporting my fundraising. Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. story:
Thanks for supporting my fundraising. Someone incredibly close to me was diagnosed with very aggressive, widespread terminal cancer just after lockdown began back in March and it has completely rocked our world. There have been so many challenges and unexpected hurdles to clear and it can be so overwhelming. Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. To have a charity that can provide so much support when you feel you are in the darkest place is such a lifeline to so many. So i have set myself a challenge and i hope, with your help, that we can raise some money so they can keep supporting people battling this cruel disease and their families. 

Thank you xxx

story:
A few months ago I found out I had breast cancer from a routine mammogram. Almost as soon as I had received my diagnosis, information was sent to me by Macmillan regarding a whole host of support that was available to me. The information given to me at my hospital appointments from Macmillan was excellent too, particularly that relating to my reconstruction options. As soon as I had undergone my surgery, a Macmillan Nurse contacted me and again when I returned home.

Thanks for supporting my fundraising and hopefully joining me (virtually) in strutting yourself to a track or two. You know I really heart dancing - I know some of you openly admit that you do too and few others of you secretly enjoy a sly shimmy in private - and that's ok. It is a great way to de-stress and I don't know anyone who after dancing, says that they regret it (except me after doing my first Oops Upside Your Head at Shane's 50th when I did my back in!). If you joined me a few years ago when I danced for a few other related causes and a couple of special men in my life, I am made up that you are still here. I have been really touched at the big love and support you have all given me over the last few months. This event is dedicated to you.

Would you like to join me for a track or 2 over zoom between 10.00 and 22.00? If so, send me your email address.

https://unitedwestream.co.uk/stream/hacienda-nye-24-hour-houseparty-united-we-stream-greater-manchester-part-3/

story:
ON 1ST JANUARY 2021 I WILL BE SHAVING MY BEARD OFF!!!

I have had my beard ever since I left the Army Reserve (Territorial Army) just over 10 years ago, as I hate shaving and no longer had a job that required me to do so!

As much as I don't want to be clean shaven, I do want to raise some money for Macmillan as they have provided Hayley and I with a lot of support so far. Macmillan have helped us financially with a grant to help pay the bills while I'm not able to work, financial advice about the best combination of benefits etc to claim and also helped arrange some counselling for us.

With this event and others in the future I am aiming to raise enough money to repay the grant, plus a bit more to cover the time spent helping us so that they can do the same for another person in the same situation in the future.

Thanks for supporting my fundraising.

Alan

story:
Welcome to Lucy and Sarah’s fundraising challenge page and thank you for taking the time to visit.

2020 has been a tough year for everyone, however much more so for Julie, a good friend and colleague of ours, who has had the added challenge of a cancer diagnosis. A particularly nasty form which has been resistant to chemotherapy - the fight goes on….

Macmillan has given her support, funding a course of counselling which has proved invaluable. So, we want to do a fundraiser for this amazing organisation that is helping everyone with cancer live as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. From the lovely Macmillan nurses to the fantastic counsellors, they are there to help every step of the way.

Our original plan of running the old year out (good riddance) and the new year in (with hope) with a marathon on a treadmill in the studio has been scuppered by the new Tier 4 rules. 

So, what would be a challenge for a couple of Pilates instructors full of Christmas pudding and turkey and no longer as young as they once were? Well, we are going to do it outside during the day on the 31st with the help of some family and four legged friends with a run around Grafham Water. And to complete the challenge, what better way to see in the New Year than an online Pilates class featuring our favourite stretches!

If you fancy joining us at 8pm on the 31st let us know and we will send you the zoom link.

In the meantime, thank you so much for your support (in advance!). Every donation will encourage us on our way to complete our challenge in support of Julie and others who are living with cancer.

We hope that 2021 is a much happier and healthier year for everyone.

Best wishes

Lucy and Sarah

Ps We will have the dogs under much better control than our photo suggests!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
To mark the 60th birthday of the British Heart Foundation (BHF), a team from Chester Road Club (CRC) will be attempting to ride 60,000 miles during 2021 - that's the entire length of your circulatory system!

Our goal is to raise £2,500 to help BHF in their vision for a world free of heart and circulatory diseases. BHF raise money to research cures and treatments, as well as working with patients and the public for better health and care.

Heart and circulatory diseases still kills 1 in 4 in the UK. In paricular I am riding in memory of Colin Watson, a CRC club member, and June Mountford-Jones, a close friend, who both died from acute heart failure during 2020.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
As you all know my uncle Marc passed away from Heart Disease, I want to raise money so more research can be done into various heart diseases!

I have a few events planned for 2021 that will definitely test me physically, will be getting plenty of training in 2021.......slim Jim pending 😂

World Heart Day is 29th September. 

Events (more may be added)

4th July 2021 - The Snowdon Challenge - 17km bike ride, followed by climbing snowdon to the summit, followed by a 5km kayak all in one go  

24th July 2021 - Coast to Coast Hike (South West, Minehead to Dawlish) 65 mile hike to be completed in one day, meaning none stop hiking for approx 22 hours  

10th October 2021 - I’m not taking part in the official race but Great Birmingham Run is scheduled for this day, so I will go out and run my own half marathon.

Date TBC - The Yorkshire Three Peaks, total of 25 miles hiking all in one go, no car journey between each peak, all walking 

It’s possible there may be other events added.

Thank you to everyone who donates, stay safe, keep smiling 😀

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
What started as endorphin runs..

As I’m sure most of you know just over 5 years ago mom died suddenly of a heart attack after what we thought was the flu. This came as a huge shock to us all and amongst all the support from family and friends; what I found really helped was an endorphin run to clear my head. On what would’ve been mom’s 50th birthday I applied to run the London marathon for the British Heart Foundation, and they have accepted me! 

The BHF have helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. Some BHF research I found particularly interesting is the development and testing of an algorithm that could be used to spot the signs of coronary artery disease in clinical practice and identify patients who may otherwise be missed.

Whilst I can’t pretend I don’t run as to this day I still love my endorphin runs... I am definitely not a long distance runner! But for such a good cause and after a mad 2020 stranger things have happened! 

This is a fab charity and whilst I and BHF would appreciate any donations I also intend on getting as creative as poss to help raise funds (just practicing my sewing skills and creativity before I start flogging my masterpieces).

I will update you on all the charitable ideas I can formulate and ofc the running aspect of the marathon!  Thanks!!

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss that has a significant impact on their daily lives. Of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone and lead lonely, isolated lives. 

Guide Dogs works for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life, for a world where being blind or partially sighted is not what defines you. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling hopes and dreams.

charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
eventName: Danny’s Great Ormond Street Hospital 100 Mile Run
story:
Hi,

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I have signed up to run 100 miles through January and would like to donate all money raised via your kind donations to Great Ormond Street Hospital, London. 

Great Ormond Street Hospital is a specialised NHS Children’s Hospital for critically ill children all over the UK. I have fortunately never needed to use or know anyone who has had to use the hospital, but the amazing work the hospital does has inspired me to give a little back. 

I am aiming to get to 100 miles across only 15 runs between 01/01/2021 and 31/01/2021.

Thank you.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Family and friends of my Grandad (Laurie) who sadly passed away on the 28th November, his funeral will take place on the 31st of December. 

 
As we are limited to the amount of people that can attend due to COVID-19 rules, we have arranged with the funeral directors of a live web feed for those who can't attend due to COVID reasons but would like to bid their farewell to this awesome legend of a gentleman.

Those who are interested in attending via live web feed on the day please inbox me with your email address and I will respond with the log in details.

My Nan has requested not to spend your money on sending flowers. Instead she has requested that money would be better given to our Justgiving charity page which will go to Great Ormand Street Children's Hospital.

Thank you all for your support, it means the world.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

story:
This January, I'm kickstarting 2021 by taking part in Running off Christmas. I'll be running 31 miles throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity. 


As some of you know, I have worked in hospitals looking after sick children for several years now. Early in 2020 I graduated as a play Specialist and started a new role at GOSH. For the last 4 years working in hospital settings I have seen the difference that donations make to a child's life In hospital. So I have decided to run 31 miles in January to support great ormond street. The money raised will go towards finding new treatments and potential cures for life limiting illnesses aswell as support for families and children whilst in hospital. 


I know how tough 2020 has been for everybody, but I am asking from the bottom of my heart for you to dig deep and donate. Even if it's just a pound, that's a pound towards a vaccine, a cure, a toy, a pound towards a parents hotel room. 


I will keep you all updated on my running... but please bear in mind... I probably haven't ran since I was in secondary school, over six years ago and even that's pushing it!

story:
This year, Great Ormond Street hospital has given and will continue to give our niece/granddaughter life saving treatment after she was diagnosed with cancer at 4 months old. As a small gesture, we have set up our Christmas Village to raised money for GOSH.

To bring a bit of festive cheer, a Christmas village has come near!

It's quite a sight for all to see, just look out for the blue tree, 

Come into the garden and have a peep, before the children go to sleep.

Put a penny in the pot, for those that don't have a lot, 

When in hospital, the girls and boys, don't have access to many toys,

With your help, imagine their smile, if they have to stay a while.

The village will be lit between 4-8pm throughout Christmas! Please do come and have a look.

story:
We are running 31 miles plus 15 this January in memory of our precious Ruby. 

Our gorgeous daughter/sister passed away in January 2019, aged 15, after a short illness. She spent her final days at Great Ormond Street and received the most amazing care from the dedicated nurses and Intensive Care Team, for which we will be forever grateful. 

Ruby had quadriplegic cerebral palsy and visited Great Ormond Street regularly throughout her life. Despite her disability, she was determined, cheeky, a real character and quite simply the light of our lives. We miss her every moment of every day, 

We have such wonderful memories of our beautiful girl and she would have found it hilarious that her Mum and Sister would be running for her like this!

Suzanne and Lola xx

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

After one of the most difficult years many of us will face in 2020, I wanted to try and bring some positivity to 2021. Whilst taking some time to reflect upon 2020, it made me think about all the times instead of going out when I had the chance, that I decided to stay inside and make up an excuse for not going for a walk/run. It made me thing of those who are sadly in hospital through no fault of their own battling terrible illnesses, especially kids who may never get to experience the world like many of us will. 

So here we are now, a new challenge for myself to raise money for charity and what better charity then Great Ormond Street?! They do such fantastic work supporting and caring for young children and their families. 

I’ve signed up to take part in the Virtual Iceland Ring Road challenge. Over the course of the next year I will be running a total of 828 miles/1,332.5km which will average out at approximately 16 miles/25.6km per week. I haven’t run since completing the Great North Run in September 2018 and am by far in the worst physical shape of my life, so there is added motivation to this fund raising effort. 

Any donations, any support towards smashing my target is much appreciated. I’ve set a target of £500 but I’m hoping to exceed this and help such a wonderful charity keep doing the amazing work they do.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

story:
This January, we are kickstarting 2021 by taking part in Running off Christmas. As Harrison (and the rest of us!) can't run we will be walking 31 miles throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity). As some know, as a family we went through one of the worst moments of our lives earlier this year, where Harrison was diagnosed with a rare condition called fibromuscular dysplasia-a condition that has affected and can continue to affect any artery in his body. He became so poorly that after receiving amazing care in Uhw, he was flown by air ambulance to Great Ormond Street Hospital where he received the most amazing, and life saving surgery and care on Eagle ward. 

Although Harrisons journey in GOSH is just beginning with more surgeries in the future, we will forever be greatful for this support, and continued support they give us when we visit every 6 months. So we have decided to try and do our part to raise some money to support the amazing work they do for the children and families they go above and beyond for every minute of every day. 

Please help us by donating what you can. It's quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the Give Now button!GOSH's patients, families and staff need your support now more than ever.

story:
This January, I'm kickstarting 2021 by taking part in Running off Christmas. I'll be running 31 miles throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity).
Finn George Tomos Cross died after 9 days of being born. He died from a rare metabolic condition called OTC in October 2020. I miss him, his brother misses him and his mother misses him.
GOSH were marvelous looking after him and helping him fight for his life so I want to help those who go through their care, so like our family, they will never have to say no to a child, they will never have to say no to trying to help.

It's quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the Give Now button!

GOSH's patients, families and staff need your support now more than ever.

story:
This January, I'm kickstarting 2021 by taking part in Running off Christmas. 

My 12 year old son, Aidan and I will be running 31 miles each so a total of 62 miles between us throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity). 

This is the second time my son has helped raise money for GOSH, he does it to support his little sister who attends the hospital for her condition,  Sturge  Weber Syndrome.

Your donations to support Great Ormond Street Hospital's life saving work will keep us going when we need it most. 

It's quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the Give Now button!

GOSH's patients, families and staff need your support now more than ever!

story: Every day brings new challenges at Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH). Every day, 618 children and young people from across the UK arrive. Every day, doctors and nurses battle the most complex illnesses, and the brightest minds come together to achieve pioneering medical breakthroughs. And every day is a chance for you to make a difference. This extraordinary hospital has always depended on charitable support to give seriously ill children the best chance to fulfil their potential. A better future for seriously ill children STARTS HERE.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my page:-

My mum, Jean Wilson was an amazing mum and a vivacious character. She was walking to the shops and caring for my 93 year old dad until 3 weeks ago.

Sadly mum started to feel confused and unwell and at 84 she was diagnosed with skin, lung and liver cancer. She died on Christmas Day at 8pm surrounded by her family. We kept her at home thanks to REACT.

I have a mum shaped hole in my heart and often find myself crying as she was my best friend . I  want to create a legacy for my lovely mum so would like to raise £500 for cancer research in the hope someone else does not have to go through what we have been through.

The photo is my mum and dad last year in happier times. My dad, their dog Sam and my husband, my son and I are lost without my mum. 

Christmas will never be the same.

eventName: Craigs virtual cycle from Lands End to John O’Groats
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I have decided to give myself a little bit of a challenge at the start of 2021  and intend to virtually cycle the length of the UK (Lands End to John O’Groats). 

I will be doing it on my exercise bike at home, starting January 1st, and to assist with the challenge I have signed up to:

https://www.theconqueror.events/lejog/?gclid=EAIaIQobChMIm4rj_s7r7QIVBOvtCh0OhgY0EAAYAiAAEgISp_D_BwE

This will track my progress as I put in the miles on my bike.

I am going to aim for completing in 12 weeks from starting. The website sets the distance as 1083miles so I will need to be doing approx. 90miles per week or 5 hours on the bike. 

I have chosen Cancer Research as my charity as I hold it close to my heart having lost my good friend and Carys’s Godfather, Bryan Polland, to cancer in 2013.

Would be much appreciated if you could sponsor me and support a great cause.

Craig

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

My lovely Mum, Jean Wilson was walking to the shops, taking the dog for a walk and caring for my 93 year old dad until 3 weeks ago. 

She had skin cancer on her head but still seemed positive, having had a skin graft. However, she shortly lost her mobility and became confused, being diagnosed with lung and liver cancer on 18th December, she passed away a week later on Christmas Day.

We kept her at home thanks to the local REACT team.

Her death was such a shock and I miss her so much.

I have a massive mum shaped hole in my heart and don’t think I will ever get used to not having my mum and best friend in my life. 

I would like to create a legacy for her by raising some money.

Christmas will never be the same.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I’ve never been the best runner and rarely go much further than 5km. But I’m 2021 I will aim to finish 12 10km runs over the year, taking part in a different 10k race each month to raise money for Cancer Research. (See events below). Every time I run more than 10km whether in a race or as part of my training I will donate £10 to this page as will my lovely husband Alan. 😁😁

Please help spur me on to reach my target of £750 by the end of 2021. 

I promise not to bung up your news feeds asking for sponsorship, but I’ll keep you updated every now and then on my progress 💪💪

My 10km race calendar: (most events I am taking part in are also raising money for other charities too) 

January - virtual event RunningWoman.com 

February - Love Welwyn run (14th) 

March - Happy Run (virtual run on international happiness day) 

April - Flitwick 10k (tbc) 

May - Hitchin 10k (23rd) BOOKED 

June - Knebworth 10k (6th) 

July - Race for Life 10k Stevenage (4th) 

August - Run Dorney 10k (29th) 

September - Stevenage 10k (19th) 

October - Standalone 10k (3rd) 

November - Hertshalf (28th) 

December - Salcey Forrest 10k (6th) Northamptonshire.

story:
Instead of a birthday card or gift for my BIG 40,  please consider donating to Marie Curie. 

Motor Neurone Disease and Cancer are very real terminal illnesses in my family. By donating to Marie Curie, you are funding care and support for people living with a terminal illness, and their families, across the UK. Please God, none of us will need to call upon this charity personally. I would be so proud to raise money for those that sadly do though. Having a January birthday, straight after Christmas (& in a pandemic) I honestly do not need cards and gifts to mark my 40th. I have abundant blessings of life, happiness, family & friends- needing nothing at all! So let’s pencil in a big charity get together when we can and please donate today. Give £3 (cost of a card) or more if you can please. Thank you and God bless. x

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Next August, I will be climbing Mount Kilimanjaro, the tallest mountain in Africa, with several other students from my university to raise money for the Marie Curie Charity. 

We believe that we need to assist people with terminal illnesses as much as we can, especially now that their lives have strongly been affected by the Covid-19 pandemic, with many patients suffering from isolation more than ever. The Marie Curie charity provides care and support to terminally ill patients and their loved ones, so that they can have the best quality of life possible in the time they have left. The Marie Curie nurses visit patients in their homes and provide symptom management, psychological support to those affected and their relatives, and they organise practical help.

To promote this work and effort, we encourage everyone to continue funding Marie Curie so that they can continue to carry out their vital work. Any donation, even a small amount, would be very much appreciated.  

Thank you for the support :)

Tom

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. 

RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.

Thank you.

We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
Ben is 8 years old and has set himself the challenge of climbing Hong Kong's tallest three peaks over three consecutive days between Christmas and New Year. He wants to raise money to tackle the climate crisis and to protect biodiversity around the world for his own and future generations.

Hong Kong's three highest peaks are Sunset Peak (869m), Lantau Peak (934m) and Tai Mo Shan (957m).  A tough challenge for a young hiker.

WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive.Your support is much appreciated.Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
Hi I’m Rose, and I have decided to participate in The Big Winter Wander to raise funds for WWF. Why you might ask? 

Nature has been a gift to offer us comfort, happiness and much-needed escape during difficult times, and now it’s our time to give back. 

Our World needs us more than ever before; our Living Planet Report shows a staggering 68% decline in wildlife populations globally. We’re destroying forests, choking oceans with plastic and causing devastating changes to the climate. Globally, we’re using all the planet’s resources faster than nature can restore itself.

That's why, on 24th January, I will be heading out for a walk with a difference – I have chosen to hike up Blencathra in the Lake District, if weather permits, or another smaller mountain yet to be confirmed if the conditions are too risky for my main choice. If you too wish to join me you can donate to participate, or you can simply just donate here to show your support and love for our beloved Planet. My aim will be to help WWF protect wildlife in the UK, and around the world. 100% of all proceeds go to WWF who are grateful for any donations whether small or large. Because even small donations when multiplied by many, make a significant difference and impact. 

IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice there's less wildlife than there used to be. That’s because half of all UK species are in decline, we’re losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, I will be helping WWF raise funds, and campaign towards protecting our beautiful Wildlife and Nature here in the UK, and all around the World. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

Thank you so much for your support and caring for our Planet...which is desperately needing our help. OUR FUTURE IS NOW!

Rose

charity.description: Oxfam is a global movement of people who won’t live with the injustice of poverty. Together we save lives in disasters. We help people build better lives for themselves. We speak out on the big issues, like inequality and climate change. And we won’t stop until we end poverty for everyone. Join us
charity.name: Oxfam
story:
Climate change is affecting millions of the worlds poorest people, right now. More frequent and extreme weather is destroying homes, and wrecking lives. The people who have done the least to cause the climate emergency are being hit the hardest this is an injustice that can and must be stopped.

Oxfam is protecting families forced to flee their homes, supporting those hit by changing weather, making sure children have a chance of a future free from poverty and responding to the deadly threat of coronavirus. Through all of this, we rely on brilliant supporters like you to make sure our dedicated teams can be where they're needed most. We couldn't do our work without you.

Every donation, no matter how big or small, makes a difference. 

Together, we won't live with poverty.

Think about donating the price of a bottle of water or twenty .... Evian darlings not Lidl... 

  Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across Ethiopia. Together, we will bring clean water to 50,000 people in Ethiopia and thousands more around the world, helping them change their own lives, forever. charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story:
Hi I'm Jordan, as many of you know there are a variety of challenges during different months of the year offering the opportunity to fundraise for a charity whilst improving your health and well being.

The most common challenge throughout the month of January is 'dry January' which involves the participants giving up alcohol. As I do not drink alcohol as often as I used to (Uni student life), I have decided to challenge myself to give up drinking everything and stick to purely drinking water. 

This will be a huge challenge for me as I love my cups of tea and coca cola.

All money raised throughout this will be donated to Water Aid.

Here in the UK are fortunate to have fresh clean water available to us whenever we want, unfortunately there are still countries that still do not have access to simple things as fresh water which most of us take for granted. With the help of this challenge I hope to raise money to help communities across the world have fresh clean drinking water. 

You can read more about their mission on their website 😀 

Please donate if you are able to, I know 2020 has been a challenging time for us all and  any contribution will be greatly appreciated. 

  Thank you for reading!

Jordan 👌

Not only is Just Water the ultimate detox after an over-indulgent Christmas, but by fundraising for WaterAid you'll be helping to change lives with the gift of clean water. Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across the world. If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk
